If it becomes clear to the couple that their marriage is beyond salvaging, however, the procedures to terminate the marriage are straightforward and are not subject to government review. But until then, every effort is made to bring dissatisfied spouses together to try to reconcile their differences. Disagreements are to be taken seriously because they can affect the harmony in and around the family.
As part of their efforts to reach a compromise, spouses are required to meet with a trained counselor, either from within the family or outside.
Co-operation is required on both sides. The key element in reaching a compromise is respect, respect, and more respect. In the absence of a feeling of respect, we cannot move forward. The bigger the problem, the harder it is to manage. Our counsellors prefer to intervene early; the advice is: Don’t wait for the problem to become too hard. Get treatment immediately. If you are not able to cooperate, well, there is no counselling agent who can save you. Respect and sincerity always work in the end—you won’t succeed in a bad relationship.
